<br>
If you plan on making a raid yourself attend it under other people first, you'll want to know all you can before you are putting other people's enjoyment in your own hands.  If you feel like being a studious raider I'd even take notes, make a list of things the raid leaders did right, things they did wrong and what you would like to do different.  I'd do a raid at least 3 or 4 times before leading your own, simply because if something goes wrong it is now ALL on your shoulders.<br>
<br>
Be fair with the loot, don't favor friends or anything because others will remember this and it's not going to reflect upon you well.<br>
<br>
Even though by now you have hopefully done the raid yourself several times, don't assume everyone else on your raid has.  Instruct them precisely as possible, like you would a little child.  Tell them when to follow, when to stay, who to assist, who to ask for buffs etc.  It's really important to let people know where they need to be, otherwise people will be confused and you'll sometimes have small groups (or sometimes the whole raid) wander off and aggro unwanted stuff.<br>
<br>
When you have a nasty pull it's up to you to judge the call if clerics should camp or not, if you do decide to call camp, SPAM it so they all get the message and hopefully one or two can get out.<br>
<br>
Delegate authority if possible, if you have someone else knowledgable there, put them in charge of tasks like debuffing and healing orders as well as cordinating pulls.<br>
<br>
By cordinating pulls I mean that you want to make sure stuff isn't coming when clerics don't have the mana or people aren't buffed.  Don't be afraid to have a &quot;=== mana check ===&quot; after a big fight to see if you should continue pulling or take a break.<br>
<br>
You're going to be really busy, people will be asking you directions often, who to do this, who to that, people will ask you about loot, if their friend can join etc. etc. etc. etc. etc.  The people already on your raid come first, only take the time to make replies if things are calm at the moment.  Put a /afk up once the raid starts, something along the lines of &quot;really busy, I'll answer you when I can&quot; will help people be more understanding.<br>
<br>
I think planning is going to be the biggest thing though, make sure you're going to have the right people, and they and you know what to do ahead of time.<br>
<br>
Well that's all I have off the top of my head Soek, good luck leading your own raids matey! <p><TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=0 CELLSPACING=0>
